and I turned on “Don’t keep Activities” and suddenly all the misbehavior our testers were seeing became apparent to me
<@U08GFT5V5>: I could just tell them to download more RAM
instead I’m writing a lengthy issue on our GitHub tracker to explain how to test this for themselves

by save and restore you simply mean onSaveInstance etc

<@U04TK850N>: to be fair, Google should really decouple the flashlight from the camera
the app does have a flashlight control in that activity, but it's kinda hidden
im pretty sure at a hardware level that becomes impractical
having a ‘good’ flash on a camera packed into a 4x4mm package is probably not trivial
<@U055GGAHS>: the flash is separate from the camera sensor though
and it’s exactly the problem that should be resolved in software anyway
isnt the hardware controlling both connected though
i guess what im saying is my experience with like all hardware is some of the seemingly trivial problems are actually side effects of other seemingly unrelated issues
but im not an expert on the flash in the cameras its just my guess that despite seeming like a no brainer it probably isn’t and its probably a mess
<@U055GGAHS>: it’s just another symlink in /sys, I’m sure
Fun stat: In our Android repo, I have 179 commits that add 13.5k lines and remove 33.7k lines
other engineer has 43 commits that add 36.9k lines and remove 8.2k lines
(I joined a month after she did)
so the other engineer is getting more work done than you
well at the moment she’s on the way into the office
so I can afford to slack off
I just think it’s interesting how my deletion count almost matches her addition count
and I’m _still_ trying to convince her to make smaller commits
when I got there, she was packing a bunch of unrelated changes together
as if she was just checking in everything she did for the day
I mean, _at least_ she was using version control, but still
<@U0548MM6B>: nah, she explained most of the changes she made in each message
still a pain in the butt to review though
<@U055GGAHS>: oh, I’ve protected master and our development branches on GitHub so that can’t happen anymore
and don’t checkout any other branch, that just dilutes your work
at least I was able to get her to agree to let me add my code style settings
so I asked the other engineer to explain why she hasn’t been saving/restoring state at all
and she told me she was on her way into the office and she’d ping me in 10-15 minutes
that was almost an hour ago
in our big Utility function class
that takes a String, and spits out a String
but it puts the passed String into a StringBuilder
<@U04TK850N>: still doesn’t use ‘Class’ in the name
well it could be an interface :stuck_out_tongue:
oh thats actually a good one i go back and forth on

FragmentName
ActivityName

NameFragment
NameActivity
but i catch myself doing the 2nd sometimes

There, solved that debate for ya
I usually daily do “ProjectSomethingSomethingClass” refactor into “Something"
cause then I have <usecase>Activity, <usecase>Fragment. makes it quicker to find in double-shift :smile:

```
I am aware of this issue. We are not saving state because of not getting a chance to do it yet. In my opinion, building features and releasing MVP were important than performance optimizations. Running out of memory while an app is running might happen rarely only on rather low-end devices.
I agree, we should do it, but I do not believe it’s a showstopper.
Also, moving forward if we are doing 1 Activity model then we should not be worried about this. But sure, feel free to fix this for next release.
```

a non low memory device may also kill you
